Exercise 1.2

a) write a R function for each type of graph allowing the user to generate graphs with an arbitrary number of nodes. b) Running the above R functions to show the adjacency matrix of each type of graph having not less than 100 nodes. NOTE: Graphs must be stored as R objects of class “network”

Complete Graph

n<- 100 # n is # of nodes
randomG <- rgraph(n, m=1, tprob=1, mode="digraph") # Create a random graph with n=7 nodes and tie prob = 0.5
generate <- function(randomG) {
  output <-as.network(randomG)
  add.edges(output,row(randomG)[randomG>0],col(randomG)[randomG>0])
  par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
  gplot(output,gmode="graph",vertex.cex=1,
        vertex.col=rgb(0,0,139,alpha=80,
                       maxColorValue=255),
        edge.col="grey80",edge.lwd=0.02,
         thresh=0.01,jitter=TRUE, usecurve=FALSE,mode = 'circle')
  return(output)
}
generate(randomG)

randomG <- rgraph(n, m=1, tprob=0, mode="graph") # Create a random graph with n=7 nodes and tie prob = 0.5
randomG[,1] <-randomG[1,] <- 1
generate <- function(randomG) {
  output <-as.network(randomG)
  add.edges(output,row(randomG)[randomG>0],col(randomG)[randomG>0])
  par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))

                       maxColorValue=255),

generate <- function(m) {
  output <-as.network(m)
  add.edges(output,row(m)[m>0],col(m)[m>0])
  par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
  gplot(output,gmode="graph",vertex.cex=0.6,
        vertex.col=rgb(0,0,139,alpha=80,
                       maxColorValue=255),
        edge.col="grey80",edge.lwd=0.02,
         thresh=0.01,jitter=TRUE, usecurve=FALSE, mode = 'circle')
  return(output)
}

The function edge_density of irgraph does not consider weights. If you call it on a weighted graph, it treats the graph as unweighted and returns the density:\(nb_edges / V*(V-1) for\) directed graphs, and \(nb_edges / V*(V-1) / 2 for\) undirected grapsh
